Preprocessing and splitting the dataset¶

In [2]:
mean = np.array([0.485, 0.456, 0.406])
std = np.array([0.229, 0.224, 0.225])

transform = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.ToTensor(),
    transforms.Normalize(mean, std)
])

dataset = datasets.ImageFolder('lfw', transform=transform)
train_size, val_size = int(0.7*len(dataset)), int(0.2*len(dataset))
test_size = len(dataset) - train_size - val_size
train_ds, val_ds, test_ds = torch.utils.data.random_split(dataset, [train_size, val_size, test_size])
In [3]:
class TripletDataset:
    def __init__(self, dataset):
        self.dataset = dataset
        self.labels = np.array([l for _,l in dataset])
    
    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.dataset)
    
    def __getitem__(self, i):
        anchor_img, anchor_lbl = self.dataset[i]
        
        pos_ids = np.flatnonzero(self.labels == anchor_lbl)
        neg_ids = np.flatnonzero(self.labels != anchor_lbl)
        
        pos_id = np.random.choice(pos_ids, 1).item()
        neg_id = np.random.choice(neg_ids, 1).item()
        
        pos_img, pos_lbl = self.dataset[pos_id] 
        neg_img, neg_lbl = self.dataset[neg_id]
        
        return (anchor_img, pos_img, neg_img), (anchor_lbl, pos_lbl, neg_lbl)

def unnormalize(img):
    img = img.permute(1, 2, 0) * std + mean
    img = img.clip(0, 1)
    return img

Helper Functions¶

In [9]:
def smooth(f, K=5):
    """ Smoothing a function using a low-pass filter (mean) of size K """
    kernel = np.ones(K) / K
    f = np.concatenate([f[:int(K//2)], f, f[int(-K//2):]])  # to account for boundaries
    smooth_f = np.convolve(f, kernel, mode="same")
    smooth_f = smooth_f[K//2: -K//2]  # removing boundary-fixes
    return smooth_f


def save_model(ckp_dir, model, optimizer, epoch, stats):
    if not os.path.exists(ckp_dir):
        os.makedirs(ckp_dir)
    savepath = os.path.join(ckp_dir, f'checkpoint_epoch_{epoch}.pt')
    torch.save({
        'epoch': epoch,
        'model_state_dict': model.state_dict(),
        'optimizer_state_dict': optimizer.state_dict(),
        'stats': stats
    }, savepath)


def load_model(model, optimizer, pt_path):
    checkpoint = torch.load(pt_path)
    model.load_state_dict(checkpoint['model_state_dict'])
    optimizer.load_state_dict(checkpoint['optimizer_state_dict'])
    epoch = checkpoint["epoch"]
    stats = checkpoint["stats"]
    return epoch, stats


def count_model_params(model):
    num_params = sum(p.numel() for p in model.parameters() if p.requires_grad)
    return num_params


def visualize_progress(train_loss, val_loss, start=0):
    """ Visualizing loss and accuracy """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,3)
    fig.set_size_inches(24,5)

    smooth_train = smooth(train_loss, 31)
    ax[0].plot(train_loss, c="blue", label="Loss", linewidth=3, alpha=0.5)
    ax[0].plot(smooth_train, c="red", label="Smoothed Loss", linewidth=3, alpha=1)
    ax[0].legend(loc="best")
    ax[0].set_xlabel("Iteration")
    ax[0].set_ylabel("CE Loss")
    ax[0].set_yscale("linear")
    ax[0].set_title("Training Progress (linear)")
    
    ax[1].plot(train_loss, c="blue", label="Loss", linewidth=3, alpha=0.5)
    ax[1].plot(smooth_train, c="red", label="Smoothed Loss", linewidth=3, alpha=1)
    ax[1].legend(loc="best")
    ax[1].set_xlabel("Iteration")
    ax[1].set_ylabel("CE Loss")
    ax[1].set_yscale("log")
    ax[1].set_title("Training Progress (log)")

    smooth_val = smooth(val_loss, 31)
    N_ITERS = len(val_loss)
    ax[2].plot(np.arange(start, N_ITERS)+start, val_loss[start:], c="blue", label="Loss", linewidth=3, alpha=0.5)
    ax[2].plot(np.arange(start, N_ITERS)+start, smooth_val[start:], c="red", label="Smoothed Loss", linewidth=3, alpha=1)
    ax[2].legend(loc="best")
    ax[2].set_xlabel("Iteration")
    ax[2].set_ylabel("CE Loss")
    ax[2].set_yscale("log")
    ax[2].set_title(f"Valid Progress")

Models, Loss and Trainer implementation¶

In [10]:
class NormLayer(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
    
    def forward(self, x):
        x_normalized = x / torch.norm(x, dim=-1, keepdim=True)
        return x_normalized
In [11]:
class SiameseModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, in_spatial, emb_dim=32, channels=[3, 16, 16, 32, 32]):
        super().__init__()
        n_layers = len(channels) - 1
        
        # convolutional feature extractor
        cnn = []
        for i in range(n_layers):
            cnn.append( nn.Conv2d(in_channels=channels[i], out_channels=channels[i+1], kernel_size=3, padding=1) )
            cnn.append( nn.BatchNorm2d(channels[i+1]))
            cnn.append( nn.ReLU() )
            cnn.append( nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2) )
            cnn.append( nn.Conv2d(in_channels=channels[i+1], out_channels=channels[i+1], kernel_size=3, padding=1) )
            cnn.append( nn.BatchNorm2d(channels[i+1]))
            cnn.append( nn.ReLU() )
        self.cnn = nn.Sequential(*cnn)
        
        # fully connected embedder
        flat_dim = int(channels[-1] * (in_spatial[0] / (2**n_layers)) * (in_spatial[0] / (2**n_layers)))
        self.fc = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Flatten(),
            nn.Linear(7200, 512),
            nn.Tanh(),
            nn.Linear(512, emb_dim),
            NormLayer())
            
    def forward_one(self, x):
        x = self.cnn(x)
        x_emb_norm = self.fc(x)
        return x_emb_norm
    
    def forward(self, anchor, positive, negative):
        anchor_emb = self.forward_one(anchor)
        positive_emb = self.forward_one(positive)
        negative_emb = self.forward_one(negative)
        return anchor_emb, positive_emb, negative_emb
In [12]:
class SiameseResnetModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, emb_dim=32):
        super().__init__()
        
        self.resnet_18 = models.resnet18(pretrained=True)
        self.resnet_18.fc = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(self.resnet_18.fc.in_features, 128),
            nn.Tanh(),
            nn.Linear(128, emb_dim),
            NormLayer())
    
    def forward_one(self, x):
        return self.resnet_18(x)
    
    def forward(self, anchor, positive, negative):
        anchor_emb = self.resnet_18(anchor)
        positive_emb = self.resnet_18(positive)
        negative_emb = self.resnet_18(negative)
        return anchor_emb, positive_emb, negative_emb
In [13]:
class TripletLoss(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, margin):
        super().__init__()
        self.margin = margin
        
    def forward(self, anchor, positive, negative):
        # L2 distances
        d_ap = (anchor - positive).pow(2).sum(dim=-1)
        d_an = (anchor - negative).pow(2).sum(dim=-1)
        
        # triplet loss function
        loss = (d_ap - d_an + self.margin)
        loss = torch.maximum(loss, torch.zeros_like(loss))
        
        loss = torch.mean(loss)
            
        return loss
In [14]:
class Trainer:
    def __init__(self, model, epochs, ckp_dir):
        self.model = model
        self.criterion = TripletLoss(margin=0.2)
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(self.model.parameters(), lr=9e-5, weight_decay=1e-5)
        self.model.to(device)
        self.ckp_dir = ckp_dir
        
        self.train_loss = []
        self.valid_loss = []
    
    @torch.no_grad()
    def valid_step(self):
        curr_losses = []
        for (anchors, positives, negatives), _ in val_loader:   
            anchors = anchors.to(device)
            positives = positives.to(device)
            negatives = negatives.to(device)
            anchor_emb, positive_emb, negative_emb = self.model(anchors, positives, negatives)
            loss = self.criterion(anchor_emb, positive_emb, negative_emb)
            curr_losses.append(loss.item())
        return curr_losses
    
    def fit(self):
        progress_bar = tqdm(total=self.epochs)
        
        self.model.eval()
        curr_losses = self.valid_step()
        self.valid_loss.extend(curr_losses)
        print(f"Valid loss before training: Loss={np.mean(curr_losses)}")
        
        for i in range(self.epochs):
            self.model.train()
            for j, ((anchors, positives, negatives), _) in enumerate(train_loader):     
                # setting inputs to GPU
                anchors = anchors.to(device)
                positives = positives.to(device)
                negatives = negatives.to(device)
                
                # forward pass and triplet loss
                anchor_emb, positive_emb, negative_emb = self.model(anchors, positives, negatives)
                loss = self.criterion(anchor_emb, positive_emb, negative_emb)
                self.train_loss.append(loss.item())
                
                # optimization
                self.optimizer.zero_grad()
                loss.backward()
                self.optimizer.step()
            
                # updating progress bar
                progress_bar.set_description(f"Train Epoch {i}, Iteration {j}: Loss={round(loss.item(),5)})")
                
            self.model.eval()
            curr_losses = self.valid_step()
            self.valid_loss.extend(curr_losses)
            print(f"Valid loss @ epoch {i}: Loss={np.mean(curr_losses)}")
            
            stats = {
                "train_loss": self.train_loss,
                "valid_loss": self.valid_loss
            }
            
            save_model(self.ckp_dir, self.model, self.optimizer, i, stats)

def get_color():
    return np.random.random(), np.random.random(), np.random.random() 

def display_projections(points, labels, ax, color_map):
    for l in np.unique(labels):
        idx = np.where(l==labels)
        if len(idx[0]) > 5:  # display only the classes that have more than 5 sample images in the test dataset
            ax.scatter(points[idx, 0], points[idx, 1], c=[color_map[l]])
In [24]:
def get_test_emb(model):
    embs = []
    with torch.no_grad():
        for (anchor, _, _), (_,_, _) in test_loader:
            anchor = anchor.to(device)
            anchor_emb = model.forward_one(anchor)
            embs.append(anchor_emb.cpu())
    embs = np.concatenate(embs)
    return embs

Comment¶

The TriNet Siamese model which has Resnet backbone performs better because the feature extractor is already trained and we are fine-tuning the model in our 20 epochs, while the TriNet Siamese model initialized with random weights needs much more epochs to converge because we are training the whole network from scratch. We can also see this from the graphs from the training and validation processes.

The dataset has 9269 training classes, 2648 validation classes and 1325 classes. This fact might be a reason why the training is not as successful as the training presented on MNIST Fashion dataset which has 10 classes.

Nevertheless, the tools for visualizing the test embeddings (PCA and TSNE) show us that the model has learned. For making clearer scatter plot, we only show the embeddings from classes that have more than 5 images in the test set.
